"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029319","Women and Equalities","false","2019-01-10","<p>In common with other such Plans which it has published, the EHRC’s Strategic Plan 2016-19 sets priority areas and intended actions for the Commission’s own work over the three years in question, but does not make recommendations either for Government or for other EHRC stakeholders. The relevant Priority Area (“Citizenship and Democracy”) of the EHRC’s Strategic Plan 2016-19 accordingly commits it to <em>“focus on delivering improvements in relation to political representation and civic participation; anti-extremism and anti-terrorism legislation and surveillance powers; and freedom of expression and freedom to associate in a trade union.”</em></p><p>The Government notes these commitments, but has not made an assessment of their merits in tackling the barriers facing women in politics and public life, or of whether they support aspects of the Equality Act 2010 such as Section 106. It is for the EHRC, as an independent public authority, to progress the commitments as it sees fit.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","204521","2019-01-10T18:02:43.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029319/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029319/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2018-12-20","Females: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of the recommendations in the Equality and Human Rights Commission’s strategic plan 2016-19 on tackling the barriers facing women in politics and public life.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","204520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029320","Women and Equalities","false","2019-01-10","<p>In common with other such Plans which it has published, the EHRC’s Strategic Plan 2016-19 sets priority areas and intended actions for the Commission’s own work over the three years in question, but does not make recommendations either for Government or for other EHRC stakeholders. The relevant Priority Area (“Citizenship and Democracy”) of the EHRC’s Strategic Plan 2016-19 accordingly commits it to <em>“focus on delivering improvements in relation to political representation and civic participation; anti-extremism and anti-terrorism legislation and surveillance powers; and freedom of expression and freedom to associate in a trade union.”</em></p><p>The Government notes these commitments, but has not made an assessment of their merits in tackling the barriers facing women in politics and public life, or of whether they support aspects of the Equality Act 2010 such as Section 106. It is for the EHRC, as an independent public authority, to progress the commitments as it sees fit.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","204520","2019-01-10T18:02:43.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029320/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029320/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029320/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2018-12-20","Political Parties: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what assessment she has made of whether the recommendations of the Equality and Human Rights Commission’s strategic plan 2016-19 support key parts of the Equalities Act 2010 such as the implementation of section 106 on the Information about diversity in range of candidates.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","204521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029321","Department for Education","false","2019-01-08","<p>Information on every local authority’s demand and spend in children’s services are published in the department’s statistical first releases and brought together in our local authority interactive tool: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-authority-interactive-tool-lait" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-authority-interactive-tool-lait</a>.</p><p>Birmingham’s core spending power for 2018 to 2019 is £888.3 million and is rising to £888.6 million in 2019 to 2020.</p><p>My right hon. Friend, the Prime Minister and my right hon. Friend, the Chancellor of the Exchequer have agreed that all long-term spending decisions are for the Spending Review, which will take place later this year.</p><p>The department is working alongside the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government and the sector as part of the fair funding review of relative needs and resources to develop a robust, up-to-date approach to funding distribution for children's services, which will determine new baseline funding allocations for local authorities in England in 2020 to 2021.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","204523","2019-01-08T18:11:32.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029321/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029321/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029321/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-20","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of level of funding from the public purse required by Birmingham City Council to deliver children’s services in (a) 2018-19, (b) 2019-20, and (c) 2020-21.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","204522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029322","Department for Education","false","2019-01-08","<p>Information on every local authority’s demand and spend in children’s services are published in the department’s statistical first releases and brought together in our local authority interactive tool: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-authority-interactive-tool-lait" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-authority-interactive-tool-lait</a>.</p><p>Birmingham’s core spending power for 2018 to 2019 is £888.3 million and is rising to £888.6 million in 2019 to 2020.</p><p>My right hon. Friend, the Prime Minister and my right hon. Friend, the Chancellor of the Exchequer have agreed that all long-term spending decisions are for the Spending Review, which will take place later this year.</p><p>The department is working alongside the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government and the sector as part of the fair funding review of relative needs and resources to develop a robust, up-to-date approach to funding distribution for children's services, which will determine new baseline funding allocations for local authorities in England in 2020 to 2021.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","204522","2019-01-08T18:11:32.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029322/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029322/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029322/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-20","Social Services: Birmingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the likely demand for children’s services in Birmingham in (a) 2018-19, (b) 2019-20, and (c) 2020/21.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","204523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029323","Home Office","false","2019-01-14","<p>There is currently no provision in the Immigration Rules for Unaccompanied children who were granted asylum in the UK to sponsor family members to make applications for family reunion outside of the immigration rules.</p><p>Allowing children to sponsor family members could create further incentives for more children to be encouraged, or even forced, to leave their family and risk hazardous journeys to the UK to sponsor relatives. This plays into the hands of criminal gangs who exploit vulnerable people and goes against our safeguarding responsibilities.</p><p>The Government believes the best interests of children are reflected in remaining with their families, claiming asylum in the first safe country they reach that is the fastest route to safety and relying on resettlement schemes to travel safely.</p><p>Available information relates to refugee family reunion applications received in total, from each nationality and how many were accepted in 2018 is published in the quarterly Immigration Statistics at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-year-ending-september-2018/list-of-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-year-ending-september-2018/list-of-tables</a></p><p>All those issued a family reunion visa are granted leave to enter or remain in the United Kingdom, not asylum. The family reunion application process does not require an assessment of the applicant’s international protection needs. It is the family member in the UK that is required to have been granted refugee status or Humanitarian Protection.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-01-14T16:16:37.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029323/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029323/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029323/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-12-20","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October 2018 to Question 179213 on Asylum: Children, how many of the of the unaccompanied children who were granted asylum in the UK in 2017 made applications for refugee family reunion outside of the immigration rules; and how many of those applications were granted by (a) the Home Office and (b) an immigration judge.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","204505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029324","Home Office","false","2019-01-14","<p>In accordance with the public sector equality duty under section 149 of the Equality Act 2010, the Government has had due regard to the impacts of the EU Settlement Scheme on those who share a protected characteristic.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-01-14T16:28:57.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029324/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029324/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029324/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-12-20","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether his Department has carried out an equality impact assessment on the EU Settlement Scheme.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","204506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029325","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-01-08","<p>The Office for Product Safety and Standards is undertaking a review of the actions taken by Whirlpool in relation to its modification programme and we will report to the House in due course.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-01-08T09:23:01.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029325/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029325/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029325/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-12-20","Whirlpool Corporation: Tumble Dryers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate the Office for Product Safety and Standards has made of the number of modifications that Whirlpool has made to the dryers referenced in its November 2015 safety announcement to date.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","204439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029326","Cabinet Office","false","2019-01-08","<p>Under the Civil Service Management Code, the conduct of civil servants is a matter for individual departments.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2019-01-08T10:14:59.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029326/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029326/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-12-20","Civil Servants: Reviews","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 19 December 2018 to Question 193470 on Ministers: Resignations, which Department monitors the number of independent reviews commissioned by the civil service into the behaviour and actions of civil servants.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","204502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029327","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-01-11","<p>HM Treasury has already allocated over £4.2 billion of additional funding to departments and the devolved administrations for EU exit preparations so far. This includes the £1.5 billion of additional funding HM Treasury announced at Autumn Budget 2017 for 2018/19. A full breakdown of how this was allocated to departments can be found in the Chief Secretary’s Written Ministerial Statement, HCWS540:</p><p><a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2018-03-13/HCWS540/" target="_blank">https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2018-03-13/HCWS540/</a>.</p><p>This money will be paid out in Supplementary Estimates 18/19 later this financial year.</p><p> </p><p>This funding was not allocated specifically for planning for the UK leaving the EU without a deal.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2019-01-11T11:56:37.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029327/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029327/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029327/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-12-20","Northern Ireland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how much funding from the public purse has been allocated to her Department for financial year 2018-19 for planning for the UK leaving the EU without a deal; and how much of that funding has been spent.","false","Biography information for Esther McVey","Tatton","Esther McVey","204497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029328","Scotland Office","false","2019-01-10","<p>HM Treasury has already allocated over £4.2 billion of additional funding to departments and the devolved administrations for EU exit preparations so far. This includes the £1.5 billion of additional funding HM Treasury announced at Autumn Budget 2017 for 2018/19. A full breakdown of how this was allocated to departments can be found in the Chief Secretary’s Written Ministerial Statement, HCWS540:</p><p><a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2018-03-13/HCWS540/" target="_blank"><strong>https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2018-03-13/HCWS540/</strong></a>.</p><p>This money will be paid out in Supplementary Estimates 18/19 later this financial year.</p><p> </p><p>The Office holds no estimate of what it has spent on no deal preparations which can readily be separated from other EU exit and devolution work in general.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2019-01-10T10:45:19.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029328/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029328/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029328/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-12-20","Scotland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how much funding from the public purse has been allocated to his Department for financial year 2018-19 for planning for the UK leaving the EU without a deal; and how much of that funding has been spent.","false","Biography information for Esther McVey","Tatton","Esther McVey","204498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029329","Wales Office","false","2019-01-10","<p>HM Treasury has already allocated over £4.2 billion of additional funding to departments and the devolved administrations for EU exit preparations so far. This includes the £1.5 billion of additional funding HM Treasury announced at Autumn Budget 2017 for 2018/19. A full breakdown of how this was allocated to departments can be found in the Chief Secretary’s Written Ministerial Statement, HCWS540:</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2018-03-13/HCWS540/" target="_blank">www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2018-03-13/HCWS540/</a>.</p><p>This money will be paid out in Supplementary Estimates 18/19 later this financial year.</p><p> </p><p>Work to prepare for a successful EU exit is a key priority for the Office of the Secretary of State for Wales. The Office holds no estimate of what it has spent on no deal exit preparations which can be readily separated from other EU exit and devolution work.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams",,"2019-01-10T10:48:27.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029329/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029329/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029329/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2018-12-20","Wales Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how much funding from the public purse has been allocated to his Department for financial year 2018-19 for planning for the UK leaving the EU without a deal; and how much of that funding has been spent.","false","Biography information for Esther McVey","Tatton","Esther McVey","204499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029330","Women and Equalities","false","2019-01-10","<p>HM Treasury has already allocated over £4.2 billion of additional funding to departments and the devolved administrations for EU exit preparations so far. This includes the £1.5 billion of additional funding HM Treasury announced at Autumn Budget 2017 for 2018/19. A full breakdown of how this was allocated to departments can be found in the Chief Secretary’s Written Ministerial Statement, HCWS540, laid on the 13th March (<a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2018-03-13/HCWS540/" target="_blank">https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2018-03-13/HCWS540/</a>). This money will be paid out in Supplementary Estimates 18/19 later this financial year.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-01-10T18:03:51.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029330/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029330/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029330/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2018-12-20","Government Equalities Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how much funding from the public purse has been allocated to her Department for financial year 2018-19 for planning for the UK leaving the EU without a deal; and how much of that funding has been spent.","false","Biography information for Esther McVey","Tatton","Esther McVey","204500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029331","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-01-07","<p>The Social Housing Green Paper asked if new safety measures in the private rented sector, such as requirements to install carbon monoxide alarms, should be extended to social housing. Alongside this, the Government is carrying out a review to establish whether requirements to install carbon monoxide (CO) alarms in private rented properties should be extended to any fuel burning appliance and social housing. The findings of this review are being considered alongside responses to the Social Housing Green Paper. We plan to set out the Government response to the Green Paper in Spring 2019.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2019-01-07T15:53:30.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029331/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029331/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029331/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-12-20","Carbon Monoxide: Poisoning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to protect social housing tenants from carbon monoxide poisoning; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","204501"
