"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029333","Department for International Development","false","2019-01-10","<p>DFID is aware of reports that USAID is currently unable to support coexistence projects in the West Bank and Gaza. The UK supports coexistence work both within green line Israel and across the Israel-OPTs boundary. All types of coexistence work can be valuable and help to foster greater understanding between communities from both sides of the conflict. Ultimately, however, the only way to achieve lasting coexistence is through a negotiated two-state solution that ends the occupation and delivers peace for both Israelis and Palestinians.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2019-01-10T15:30:29.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029333/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029333/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029333/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-12-20","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of the recently reported reductions in funding from the US to co-existence projects in Israel-Palestine on peace efforts in that region.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","204610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029334","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-01-08","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions is supportive of the Breathing Space policy. Departmental officials are working with HM Treasury to understand how the policy could apply to benefit related debts and we will provide a response to the public consultation in line with the end of January deadline.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-01-08T13:00:04.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029334/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029334/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029334/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-12-20","Department for Work and Pensions: Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans the Government has to include debts owed to her Department in its new breathing space scheme.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","204424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029335","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-01-10","<p>The Department collects and publishes its workforce management information each month. These details can be found at the following link.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dwp-workforce-management-information" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dwp-workforce-management-information</a></p><p> </p><p>The Department’s headcount is collected and reported as at the last day of each month. On 30 June 2016 the Department’s headcount was 84,226 and on 30 November 2018 it was 82,827.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-01-10T15:55:02.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029335/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029335/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029335/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-12-20","Department for Work and Pensions: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many staff were employed in her Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029336","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-01-08","<p>At the end of November 2018 there were 3,955 people working in the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (full time equivalent), figures are not reported at the mid-month point.</p><p> </p><p>At the end of June 2016 this figure was 3,702, however the Machinery of Government change process was not fully concluded until March 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Figures include staff on payroll and contingent workers but excludes staff not on payroll, fast streamers or any staff not paid for by BEIS.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2019-01-08T09:23:15.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029336/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029336/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029336/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-12-20","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029337","Department for International Development","false","2019-01-09","<p>As at 20 December 2018 DFID employed 2728 Home Civil Servants (HCS), 2022 HCS were employed on 23 June 2016.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-01-09T14:33:09.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029337/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029337/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029337/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-12-20","Department for International Development: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many staff were employed in her Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029338","Department for International Trade","false","2019-01-14","<p>When the Department for International Trade (DIT) was formed in July 2016, the number of staff was 2,504. This figure includes staff working at UK Export Finance (UKEF).</p><p> </p><p>The number of staff working for the Department for International Trade and UKEF as at 31 December 2018 is 3,925.</p><p> </p><p>The number of people working for the department is calculated at the end of each month. Therefore, the closest dataset available has been shown.</p><p> </p><p>The figures above include all people engaged in DIT and UKEF business activities. This includes employees (including those working overseas), contractors and those on loan from other government departments or seconded from organisations external to the Civil Service.</p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery",,"2019-01-14T15:30:34.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029338/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029338/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029338/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-12-20","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029339","Department for Transport","false","2019-01-14","<p>In response to your request, the number of staff employed by the Department and its agencies (DfT Central Department, the Driver Vehicle &amp; Licensing Agency, the Driver &amp; Vehicle Services Agency, the Maritime &amp; Coastguard Agency and the Vehicle Certification Agency) on the respective dates are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>30th June 2016</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>30th November 2018</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Headcount</p></td><td><p>FTE</p></td><td><p>Headcount</p></td><td><p>FTE</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DfTc</p></td><td><p>2084</p></td><td><p>2021.8</p></td><td><p>2674</p></td><td><p>2598.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DVLA</p></td><td><p>6244</p></td><td><p>5548.2</p></td><td><p>6068</p></td><td><p>5346.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DVSA</p></td><td><p>4527</p></td><td><p>4273.2</p></td><td><p>4827</p></td><td><p>4559.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>MCA</p></td><td><p>1015</p></td><td><p>963.8</p></td><td><p>1143</p></td><td><p>1095.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>VCA</p></td><td><p>155</p></td><td><p>145.9</p></td><td><p>180</p></td><td><p>170.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>14025</p></td><td><p>12952.9</p></td><td><p>14892</p></td><td><p>13770.6</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Please note, the figures represented have been taken from end of month reports and as there is currently no report available for December 2018. The figures used are at 30<sup>th</sup> November 2018. The figures represent pay staff and do not include contractors and other non-pay employees.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2019-01-14T12:27:02.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029339/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029339/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029339/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-12-20","Department for Transport: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029340","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-01-10","<p>The number of staff employed in the Department on the dates requested are shown below.</p><p> </p><p>20 December 2018</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Military Strength</p></td><td><p>196,120</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Civilian Employees</p></td><td><p>47,940</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>244,060</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>23 June 2016</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Military Strength</p></td><td><p>201,350</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Civilian</p></td><td><p>46,410</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>247,760</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The military figures include both trained and untrained Service personnel, Ghurkhas</p><p>and the Royal Gibraltar Regiment.</p><p>All figures have been rounded to the nearest 10, numbers ending in 5 have been rounded to the nearest multiple of 20 to avoid systematic bias.</p><p>Totals have been rounded separately and therefore may not equal the sum of their rounded parts.</p><p>- zero or rounded to zero</p><p>The civilian figures are MOD Main personnel, including DE&amp;S. Personnel from DSTL, the Royal Fleet Auxiliary, other agencies and arm’s length bodies are not included.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2019-01-10T15:10:36.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029340/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029340/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029340/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-12-20","Ministry of Defence: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029341","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-09","<p>On 20 December 2018 the Department employed 1,589 civil servants. On 23 June 2016 the Department employed 1,974 civil servants.</p><p> </p><p>Civil servants are defined as employees, fixed term appointments and loans into the Department. These figures do not include agency workers, contractors and consultants.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-01-09T12:24:40.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029341/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029341/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","Department of Health and Social Care: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029342","Scotland Office","false","2019-01-10","<p>The Office of the Secretary of Scotland does not hold staffing information at mid-point monthly dates; information is recorded at month end only.</p><p>On 30 June 2016, there were 67.0 FTE staff in post, and on 31 December 2018 there were 74.4 FTE staff in post.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2019-01-10T10:43:35.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029342/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029342/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029342/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2018-12-20","Scotland Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029343","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-01-11","<p>The total number of staff employed by Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs on 31 May 2016, 30 June 2016 and 30 November 2018 are shown below;</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Month/Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Headcount</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31 May 2016</p></td><td><p>1,693</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>30 June 2016</p></td><td><p>1,693</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>30 November 2018</p></td><td><p>4,168</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Staff in Post Data is only run as at the end of each month in order to provide information for published statutory returns. The data provided is in line with the figures published at <a href="https://data.gov.uk/dataset/workforce-management-information-defra" target="_blank">Data.gov.uk - https://data.gov.uk/dataset/workforce-management-information-defra</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Along with other public sector employers, the department provides data to the Office of National statistics for the “Quarterly Public Sector Employment Survey”. The most recent publication was 11 December showing data as at the end of September 2018 and can be found here - <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/publicsectoremployment/september2018" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/publicsectoremployment/september2018</a> .</p><p> </p><p>ONS data for earlier reference dates can be found here – <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/publicsectoremployment/previousReleases" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/publicsectoremployment/previousReleases</a></p><p> </p><p>The Staff in Post data has to go through a lengthy resource intensive verification process to eliminate a high proportion of errors. To provide data as at 20 December would incur disproportionate costs.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2019-01-11T13:00:36.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029343/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029343/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-12-20","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029344","Home Office","false","2019-01-14","<p>Home Office publish monthly workforce management information on gov.uk - links provided below.</p><p>2010 to 2017: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/structure-and-salaries-series" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/structure-and-salaries-series</a></p><p>January to October 2018: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/workforce-management-information-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/workforce-management-information-2018</a></p><p>Figures for November 2018 and June 2016 are provided in the table 1 attached.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-01-14T16:21:14.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029344/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029344/answer","Table-1.xlsx","Table-1.xlsx","Table 1 - Figs Nov 2018-June 2016 ","Table 1 - Figs Nov 2018-June 2016 ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029344/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-12-20","Home Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029345","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-14","<p>It is standard practice for the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) to calculate headcount numbers on the last working day of each month. Therefore, our December 2018 figures are not yet available.</p><p>As of the 30<sup>th</sup> November 2018, the FCO has 4788 (4721 FTE) UK-based staff. As of the 30<sup>th</sup> June 2016, the FCO had 4331 (4253 FTE) UK-based staff.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2019-01-14T16:38:44.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029345/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029345/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-12-20","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029346","Wales Office","false","2019-01-08","<p>The Office of the Secretary of State for Wales (OSSW) is not an employer in its own right and the Ministry of Justice (MoJ) provide employment services on our behalf. The number of Civil Servants working for OSSW on the requested dates is shown below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of staff</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>a) 20 December 2018</p></td><td><p>44</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>b) 23 June 2016</p></td><td><p>42</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams",,"2019-01-08T13:18:00.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029346/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029346/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2018-12-20","Wales Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029347","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-01-09","<p>The number of staff employed by the Department for Exiting the European Union is published, each month, on gov.uk as part of our transparency reporting. It can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/department-for-exiting-the-european-union-monthly-workforce-management-information-for-2017-and-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/department-for-exiting-the-european-union-monthly-workforce-management-information-for-2017-and-2018</a></p><p>The Department for Exiting the European Union was not in existence on 23 June 2016.</p><p> </p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-01-09T16:12:06.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029347/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029347/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-12-20","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029348","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-01-08","<p>The Department’s workforce statistics are published on a quarterly basis by the Office for National Statistics as part of its Quarterly Public Sector Employment estimates. Data for the two quarters in question, June 2016 and September 2018 (latest available quarterly release) can be viewed and obtained via the following link: <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/publicsectoremploymentreferencetable" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/publicsectoremploymentreferencetable</a> (table 9) in the attached xlsx files for the dates in question.</p><p>At the end of June 2016 the Department employed a reported 1,420 full-time equivalent staff in comparison with 1,890 full-time equivalent staff at the end of September 2018. Please note that these figures are rounded to the nearest ten at the point of release and do not include the Department’s Executive Agencies or non-departmental public bodies (NDPB). The difference between the two reported numbers represents a 33 per cent increase in staffing levels during the period in question. It is important to note that in March 2010 there were 2109 full-time equivalent staff working in the Department.</p><p>Please note that the numbers reported to ONS are based on directly employed officials where the Department bears at least 50 per cent of salary costs through its payroll. Staff employed directly by the Department who are on an unpaid leave of absence, or paid on a reimbursed basis, are not included in management information published on GOV.UK and supplied to ONS.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2019-01-08T15:45:29.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029348/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029348/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-12-20","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029349","Treasury","false","2019-01-10","<p>Please see below the paid full time equivalent staff, using ONS definitions for the end of June 2016 and the end November 2018. This is the latest data available for each month.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>30th June 2016</p></td><td><p>30th November 2018</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Full-Time Equivalent</p></td><td><p>1223.1</p></td><td><p>1446.8</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2019-01-10T10:44:58.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029349/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029349/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029349/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-12-20","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029350","Cabinet Office","false","2019-01-08","<p>In June 2016, the number of staff employed in my Department was 2,384. In November 2018 the number of staff employed in my Department (latest workforce figures) was 6,214.</p><p>Most of the increase here (82%) is the result of the transfer of staff and functions into the Cabinet Office from other Government Departments under machinery of government changes.</p><p>As part of this Government’s commitment to transparency, my Department publishes workforce statistics each month. Information about staffing levels since June 2016 are available at</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/payroll-costs-and-non-consolidated-pay-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/payroll-costs-and-non-consolidated-pay-data</a></p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2019-01-08T10:16:05.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029350/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029350/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-12-20","Cabinet Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029351","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-01-08","<p>On 20 December 2018, there were 165 staff working in my Department. In July 2016, (the nearest date we have for June staff numbers), there were 115 staff working in my department.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2019-01-08T12:59:17.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029351/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029351/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029351/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-12-20","Northern Ireland Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many staff were employed in her Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029352","Department for Education","false","2019-01-09","<p>Staffing data are produced for the department monthly. The table below shows the number of staff employed in the department at the end of November 2018 and at the end of June 2016:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Headcount</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Full-time equivalent </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>a) November 2018</p></td><td><p>6308</p></td><td><p>6074.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>b) June 2016</p></td><td><p>3531</p></td><td><p>3395.6</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>During this period, there have been Machinery of Government changes. This included the department taking responsibility for higher and further education and for the Skills Funding Agency, which merged with the Education Funding Agency to create the Education and Skills Funding Agency.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2019-01-09T17:33:08.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029352/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029352/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-20","Department for Education: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029353","Attorney General","false","2019-01-14","<p>The table below shows the number of staff employed by the Attorney General’s Office on 20 December 2018 and 23 June 2016 respectively:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Employment Type</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>23 June 2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>20 December 2018</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Permanent</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fixed Term</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Loan In</p></td><td><p>24</p></td><td><p>24</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Secondment In</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Agency Worker</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>43</p></td><td><p>47</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2019-01-14T09:04:57.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029353/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029353/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029353/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2018-12-20","Attorney General: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029354","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-01-09","<p>In MoJ, staff data is collected monthly at month-end, as such we have provided data at the nearest available snapshot dates below:</p><p> </p><ol><li><p>70,227 FTE (Full Time Equivalent) - as at 30 November 2018</p></li><li><p>63,364 FTE – as at 30 June 2016</p><p> </p><p>The increase noted is almost exclusively in HMPPS (6,311 FTE) and predominantly in the operational line.</p></li></ol>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-01-09T17:54:46.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029354/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029354/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-12-20","Ministry of Justice: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff were employed in his Department on (a) 20 December 2018 and (b) 23 June 2016.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","204552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029355","Department for Education","false","2019-01-07","<p>The information requested is not held by the department. Local authorities must secure the provision specified in a child or young person’s Education, Health and Care (EHC) plan. Where this requires the local authority to provide additional ‘top-up’ funding, an agreement should be in place between the local authority and the institution that confirms the amount of top-up funding to be paid. This agreement does not form part of the EHC plan.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-01-07T14:44:52.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029355/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029355/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029355/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-20","Special Educational Needs: Derbyshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many school children on Education, Health and Care Plans in Derbyshire do not have extra funding allocated to their schools for their plan.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","204475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029356","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-01-07","<p>Due to the volume of data required to answer this question, the information is attached as an annex to this answer.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-01-07T15:12:56.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029356/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029356/answer","204476 Annex to SEND PQ December 2018.xls","204476 Annex to SEND PQ December 2018.xls","XLS Statistics Annex A","XLS Statistics Annex A","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029356/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-12-20","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many times a tribunal (a) has been required to meet to consider amendments, (b) found in favour of the application for amendment and (c) decided there would be no change to an Education, Health and Care Plan in each local authority area in each year since the plans were introduced.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","204476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029357","Department for Education","false","2019-01-07","<p>The number of school children and the number with an Education, Health and Care Plan are published at local authority level in the statistics publication Special Educational Needs in England: January 2018 in table 12. The publication can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/special-educational-needs-in-england-january-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/special-educational-needs-in-england-january-2018</a>.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-01-07T14:46:15.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029357/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029357/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029357/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-20","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many school children (a) are there and (b) have an Education, Health and Care Plan in each local authority area.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","204477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029358","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-14","<p>The following table is a summary of the aggregated amount spent in the main categories of National Health Service commissioner spending, as recorded centrally by NHS England, for acute, mental health, community care, continuing care and primary care in 2015-16, 2016-17 and 2017-18.</p><p> </p><p>The data was provided by NHS England. NHS England do not hold clinical commissioning group (CCG) level spending data across all of these categories for all CCGs.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Type of Care</p></td><td><p>Amount Spent 2015-16</p></td><td><p>Amount Spent 2016-17</p></td><td><p>Amount Spent 2017-2018</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Acute</p></td><td><p>£38,247 million</p></td><td><p>£40,107 million</p></td><td><p>£41,411 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mental health</p></td><td><p>£7,301 million</p></td><td><p>£7,627 million</p></td><td><p>£8,053 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Community</p></td><td><p>£7,088 million</p></td><td><p>£7,115 million</p></td><td><p>£7,348 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Continuing</p></td><td><p>£4,297 million</p></td><td><p>£4,582 million</p></td><td><p>£4,547 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Primary</p></td><td><p>£12,124 million</p></td><td><p>£13,870 million</p></td><td><p>£16,474 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2019-01-14T11:21:23.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029358/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029358/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029358/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","NHS: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much was spent in the main categories of NHS commissioner spending as recorded centrally by NHS England for (a) acute, (b) mental Health, (c) community care, (d) continuing care and (e) primary care by clinical commissioning group in (i) 2015-16, (ii) 2016-17 and (iii) 2017-18.","true","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","204632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029359","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-01-08","<p>We published a call for evidence on the future of small-scale low-carbon generation in the summer and we intend to follow this up with a consultation on proposals for future arrangements shortly.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2019-01-08T09:22:55.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029359/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029359/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-12-20","Renewable Energy: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when his Department plans to publish its proposals on recompensing small scale renewables exporting to the grid.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","204408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029360","Department for Education","false","2019-01-08","<p>Schools are autonomous institutions and therefore it is for schools to determine by how much an individual teacher’s pay should rise if they are considered eligible for progression.</p><p> </p><p>With the above in mind, it is for schools to decide how best to spend the funds allocated under the teachers’ pay grant. The Department has, however, made clear that this additional money is to fully fund an increase in pay for teachers and the Department would therefore expect schools to put it towards pay.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","204599","2019-01-08T18:18:15.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029360/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029360/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-20","Teachers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how his Department is ensuring that funds allocated under the Teachers' Pay Grant for 2018-19 are being used to fund teachers' pay and not for any other purpose.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","204598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029361","Department for Education","false","2019-01-07","<p>The information requested is not held centrally. The department does not collect data on the number of educational psychologist assessments carried out each year.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-01-07T14:47:03.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029361/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029361/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-20","Educational Psychology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many educational psychological assessments have been carried out in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","204513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029362","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-11","<p>Public Health England (PHE) was commissioned by the Department in 2018 to review trends in life expectancy and mortality in England. PHE’s review was released on 11 December 2018 and is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/recent-trends-in-mortality-in-england-review-and-data-packs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/recent-trends-in-mortality-in-england-review-and-data-packs</a></p><p> </p><p>The review summarises the findings from the commission and suggests further work that could be undertaken, by PHE or others. It provides a review of official data to advance understanding of the trends in life expectancy and mortality in England, as well as more detail on specific population groups and specific causes of death, including insight into possible explanations for the trends observed.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-01-11T12:10:18.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029362/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029362/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","Life Expectancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment he has made of trends in life expectancy.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","204558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029363","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-10","<p>This Government recognises that winter, with demand placed on services with colder weather and seasonal flu, is a challenging time for the National Health Service as it is for health services around the world. Ministers meet weekly with our systems leaders in the NHS to ensure that our services are equipped for winter to support those who need them.</p><p> </p><p>This year the Government has supported the NHS with more than £420 million of winter funding. Although we are at the start of the winter period, the latest published NHS winter operational updates show that in December there have been fewer ambulance handover delays and diverts to other accident and emergency’s compared to last year. This means ambulances spend less time at hospitals and more time on the roads reaching patients.</p><p> </p><p>On 7 January 2019, I laid a written ministerial statement <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2019-01-07/HCWS1232/" target="_blank">HCWS1232</a> which sets out our preparations to help the NHS this winter.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2019-01-10T13:41:05.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029363/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029363/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","Health Services: Weather","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of the NHS's preparations for winter.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","204559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029364","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-14","<p>The National Health Service employs record numbers of staff, in 2018 - over 1.2 million or 1,074,209 full time equivalents. This is an increase of 63,100 since May 2010, with more staff than at any other time in its 70 year history and significant growth in newly qualified staff over the period from 2010. As at 30 September 2018, there were almost 103,000 healthcare vacancies in the NHS, which are largely filled by agency and bank staff.</p><p> </p><p>In 2018 we committed to:</p><p>- increasing NHS funding by an average of 3.4% per year, meaning that by 2023/24 the NHS will receive £20.5 billion a year more than it currently does;</p><p>- giving around one million NHS staff a well-deserved pay rise, with all staff receiving at least a 3% pay increase by the end of 2018/2019;</p><p>- increasing the number of training places for doctors, nurses and midwives, with more general practitioners than ever starting training in the NHS this year; and</p><p>- we are delivering an additional 1,500 undergraduate medical places, including an additional 90 places at Hull York Medical School and as part of the expansion opening five new medical schools across England.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS Long Term Plan, published on 7 January 2019, sets out a vital strategic framework to ensure that over the next 10 years the NHS will have the staff it needs so that nurses and doctors have the time they need to care, working in a supportive culture that allows them to provide the expert compassionate care they are committed providing.</p><p> </p><p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care has commissioned Baroness Dido Harding, working closely with Sir David Behan, to lead a number of programmes to engage with key NHS interests to develop a detailed workforce implementation plan. These programmes will consider detailed proposals to grow the workforce rapidly, including consideration of additional staff and skills required, build a supportive working culture in the NHS and ensure first rate leadership for NHS staff.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","204569","2019-01-14T11:18:24.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029364/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029364/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","NHS: Vacancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment he has made of the level of staff shortages across the NHS.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","204560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029365","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-10","<p>The NHS Constitution clearly describes the right of patients to start consultant-led treatment within a maximum of 18 weeks from referral for non-urgent conditions.</p><p> </p><p>This year, the Government recognises that the standard of ensuring at least 92% of patients start consultant-led treatment within a maximum of 18 weeks is not being met. However, at present, over one million National Health Service patients start planned treatment with a consultant each month and the majority are seen and treated within a maximum of 18 weeks. Furthermore, we have reduced the number of people waiting the longest (over 52 weeks) to start treatment from almost 18,500 in 2010 to just under 3,000 in October 2018.</p><p> </p><p>For 2018/19, the Government has provided the NHS with an additional £1.6 billion to support and improve accident and emergency and elective care performance. Furthermore, the NHS Long Term Plan will set out how the NHS will develop over the coming years. This will be supported by an extra £20.5 billion a year in real terms by 2023/24.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","204567","2019-01-10T14:24:47.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029365/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029365/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","NHS: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment he has made of trends in the level of referral to treatment waiting times.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","204561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029366","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-14","<p>This Government has been clear that we do not want or expect a ‘no deal’ scenario. However, it is the duty of a responsible Government to continue to prepare for a range of potential outcomes, including the event of ‘no deal’. The Department has undertaken extensive work to prepare for a ‘no deal’ scenario, including contingency planning, and we continue to take the necessary steps to ensure the country continues to operate smoothly from the day we leave.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is working with its partners across Government, arm’s length bodies and industry, to ensure that all relevant parties are prepared for exiting the European Union. The quality and safety of patient care is paramount in our preparedness plans.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is working to mitigate the impact of any potential delays at borders if there is ‘no deal’. Our planning aims to ensure that from the day the United Kingdom leaves the EU, we will have the necessary resources in place to maintain uninterrupted supplies of medicines and medical products.</p><p> </p><p>Over the course of August, September and October 2018, the Government published a series of technical notices, eight of which are specific to the health and care sector. Since then, we have published further guidance on preparing for a ‘no deal’ scenario.</p><p> </p><p>In preparation for the possibility of a ‘no deal’ exit, the Department, with the support of NHS England and Improvement and Public Health England, has set up a national Operational Response Centre (ORC), which is structured to be able to respond to any impacts on health and social care. This will lead on responding to disruptions to delivery and co-ordinate reporting across the health and care system; the Department has a wide pool of trained staff available to support this if needed. The ORC will work with the devolved administrations to respond to United Kingdom-wide incidents where appropriate.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2019-01-14T15:58:25.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029366/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029366/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","Department of Health and Social Care: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what progress his Department has made on contingency planning for the UK leaving the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","204562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029367","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-01-07","<p>The details of which aspects of social security will be coordinated with the EU under the future relationship will be subject to negotiation with the EU.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2019-01-07T18:06:46.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029367/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029367/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-12-20","Orchestras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Draft Political Declaration setting out the framework for the future relationship between the United Kingdom and the European Union, published on 22 November, whether the reciprocal arrangements on the future rules around some defined elements of social security coordination will include UK access to the A1 system exempting UK orchestras touring in European Union countries from paying social security contributions in those countries.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","204363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029368","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-09","<p>NHS England and Health Education England (HEE) are working together with the profession to increase the general practitioner (GP) workforce. This includes measures to boost recruitment, address the reasons why GPs are leaving the profession, and encourage GPs to return to practice.</p><p> </p><p>There is a broad offer available to support GPs to remain in the National Health Service including the GP Health Service, the GP Retention Scheme, and the GP Retention Fund.</p><p> </p><p>In May 2018, NHS England launched the £10 million GP Retention Fund, comprising of the Local Retention Fund (£7 million) and the Intensive Support Areas (£3 million) which will help GPs stay in the workforce by promoting new ways of working and offering additional support.</p><p> </p><p>Recognising that workload is one of the biggest issues impacting retention, NHS England is investing £30 million in the Releasing Time for Care Programme, which aims to help practices reduce their workload through spreading awareness of innovations and facilitating local programmes.</p><p> </p><p>Getting the skills mix right in general practice is also critical in addressing workload pressures as well as in delivering appropriate patient care. This will mean bigger teams of staff, providing a wider range of care options for patients and freeing up more time for GPs to focus on those with more complex needs. As of September 2018, there were over 3,700 more clinical staff, excluding GPs, working in general practice since 2015; consisting of over 600 more nurses and over 3,000 more other direct patient care.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to this work, the General Practice Partnership Review, an independent review into the partnership model to which practices work, will deliver its final report early this year. The independent review will consider key questions around workforce and workload and make a number of recommendations with the aim of ensuring general practice remains an excellent place to work.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-01-09T15:04:10.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029368/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029368/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029368/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","General Practitioners: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent steps he has taken to improve the retention level of GPs within the NHS.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","204563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029369","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-09","<p>The Government takes the concerns around reported avoidable sight loss very seriously. Following the All Party Parliamentary Group on Eye Health and Visual Impairment’s ‘See the Light’ report, initial meetings have been held with key stakeholders to discuss the Department and NHS England’s response to the report’s recommendations and these discussions are ongoing.</p><p> </p><p>Two key initiatives, Getting it Right First Time being led by NHS Improvement and the Elective Care Transformation Programme being led by NHS England have considered, as part of their programmes, what can be done to ensure patients do not suffer unnecessary delays in follow-up care for ophthalmology.</p><p> </p><p>Action is also being taken to reduce sight loss caused by medical conditions. On diabetic retinopathy, a common complication of diabetes which can lead to sight loss, a diabetic retinopathy screening programme led by Public Health England offered screening to 2.4 million eligible people in 2015/16.</p><p> </p><p>Early detection is also key and free National Health Service sight tests are available to those at increased risk of eye disease or likely to be deterred from seeking private tests on grounds of cost.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-01-09T15:05:38.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029369/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029369/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","Visual Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to tackle preventable blindness.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","204564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029370","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-14","<p>The timescale for any assessment of the effectiveness of minimum unit pricing in Scotland will be driven by the availability of robust empirical evidence from its implementation.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-01-14T16:16:56.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029370/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029370/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","Alcoholic Drinks: Minimum Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what his timescale is for Public Health England's assessment of the effectiveness of minimum unit pricing in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","204570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029371","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-10","<p>The Government recognises the need to increase the mental health workforce to deliver its ambitious mental health transformation programme. To ensure that the National Health Service has an adequate workforce, Health Education England (HEE) published ‘Stepping Forward to 2020/21: The Mental Health Workforce Plan for England’. This plan sets out the Government’s ambition to deliver 21,000 new posts, professional and allied, across the mental health system, with the expectation that 19,000 of these places will be filled by staff employed directly by the NHS.</p><p> </p><p>The plan aims to increase the size of the mental health workforce through increased recruitment, improved retention and through development of new roles and ways of working to improve efficient use of the most qualified staff. A Mental Health Workforce Delivery Group, chaired by HEE and attended by the Department and its arm's-length bodies, was established shortly after publication to oversee implementation of the plan, through regional sustainability and transformation partnerships.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-01-10T13:52:09.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029371/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029371/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","Mental Health Services: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the capacity of the mental health workforce.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","204565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029372","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-10","<p>During this Parliament, Government has taken steps to address the immediate pressures on the social care system, including giving councils access to up to £3.6 billion more dedicated funding for adult social care this year, which councils can use to provide vital services for older people and working age disabled adults. In addition, the budget announced a further £650 million to improve social care services and help reduce pressures on the National Health Service by supporting older people, people with disabilities and children in 2019-20. An additional £55 million of capital funding in 2018-19 for the Disabled Facilities Grant to provide home aids and adaptations for disabled children and adults on low incomes was also announced at the budget.</p><p> </p><p>In the longer term the Green Paper will consider the fundamental issues facing adult social care system, while funding for future years will be settled in the Spending Review where the overall approach to funding local government will be considered in the round.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-01-10T14:23:35.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029372/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029372/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of funding for the social care of (a) older people and (b) working-age disabled adults.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","204566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029373","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-10","<p>The NHS Constitution clearly describes the right of patients to start consultant-led treatment within a maximum of 18 weeks from referral for non-urgent conditions.</p><p> </p><p>This year, the Government recognises that the standard of ensuring at least 92% of patients start consultant-led treatment within a maximum of 18 weeks is not being met. However, at present, over one million National Health Service patients start planned treatment with a consultant each month and the majority are seen and treated within a maximum of 18 weeks. Furthermore, we have reduced the number of people waiting the longest (over 52 weeks) to start treatment from almost 18,500 in 2010 to just under 3,000 in October 2018.</p><p> </p><p>For 2018/19, the Government has provided the NHS with an additional £1.6 billion to support and improve accident and emergency and elective care performance. Furthermore, the NHS Long Term Plan will set out how the NHS will develop over the coming years. This will be supported by an extra £20.5 billion a year in real terms by 2023/24.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","204561","2019-01-10T14:24:47.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029373/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029373/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","NHS: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to ensure that the pledges set out in the NHS Constitution on waiting times are met.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","204567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029374","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-11","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care has met Babylon Healthcare on two occasions including at a technology roundtable attended by various health technology companies on 18 July 2018 and at their offices on 13 September 2018.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-01-11T12:07:13.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029374/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029374/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","Babylon Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent meetings he has had with Babylon Healthcare.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","204568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029375","Department for Education","false","2019-01-08","<p>Schools are autonomous institutions and therefore it is for schools to determine by how much an individual teacher’s pay should rise if they are considered eligible for progression.</p><p> </p><p>With the above in mind, it is for schools to decide how best to spend the funds allocated under the teachers’ pay grant. The Department has, however, made clear that this additional money is to fully fund an increase in pay for teachers and the Department would therefore expect schools to put it towards pay.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","204598","2019-01-08T18:18:15.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029375/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029375/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-20","Teachers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to reports that some academies have chosen not to pay the 2018-19 teacher pay award despite receiving the Teacher's Pay Grant for that year, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that academies in receipt of the pay grant deliver the pay award to their teachers.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","204599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029376","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-14","<p>The National Health Service employs record numbers of staff, in 2018 - over 1.2 million or 1,074,209 full time equivalents. This is an increase of 63,100 since May 2010, with more staff than at any other time in its 70 year history and significant growth in newly qualified staff over the period from 2010. As at 30 September 2018, there were almost 103,000 healthcare vacancies in the NHS, which are largely filled by agency and bank staff.</p><p> </p><p>In 2018 we committed to:</p><p>- increasing NHS funding by an average of 3.4% per year, meaning that by 2023/24 the NHS will receive £20.5 billion a year more than it currently does;</p><p>- giving around one million NHS staff a well-deserved pay rise, with all staff receiving at least a 3% pay increase by the end of 2018/2019;</p><p>- increasing the number of training places for doctors, nurses and midwives, with more general practitioners than ever starting training in the NHS this year; and</p><p>- we are delivering an additional 1,500 undergraduate medical places, including an additional 90 places at Hull York Medical School and as part of the expansion opening five new medical schools across England.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS Long Term Plan, published on 7 January 2019, sets out a vital strategic framework to ensure that over the next 10 years the NHS will have the staff it needs so that nurses and doctors have the time they need to care, working in a supportive culture that allows them to provide the expert compassionate care they are committed providing.</p><p> </p><p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care has commissioned Baroness Dido Harding, working closely with Sir David Behan, to lead a number of programmes to engage with key NHS interests to develop a detailed workforce implementation plan. These programmes will consider detailed proposals to grow the workforce rapidly, including consideration of additional staff and skills required, build a supportive working culture in the NHS and ensure first rate leadership for NHS staff.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","204560","2019-01-14T11:18:24.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029376/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029376/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","NHS: Vacancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent steps he has taken to tackle NHS workforce shortages.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","204569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029377","Prime Minister","false","2019-01-14","<p>The result of the 2016 referendum on United Kingdom’s membership of the European Union. Free movement coming to an end when the United Kingdom leaves the EU is also the official position of Her Majesty’s Official Opposition (Shadow Home Secretary, the Rt Hon. Member for Hackney North and Stoke Newington (Diane Abbott), Official Report, 19 December 2018, Column 807).</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2019-01-14T17:44:33.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029377/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029377/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2018-12-20","Free Movement of People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, with reference to her oral contribution of 19 December 2018, Official Report, column 786, what the evidential basis is for the statement that will of people in the EU referendum 2016 was to end free movement; and if she will place a copy of that research in the Library.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","204601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029378","Department for Education","false","2019-01-09","<p>A Teachers’ Pay Grant will be paid to all maintained schools and academies this year and next. The grant will total £187 million in 2018-19 and £321 million in 2019-20. The methodology underpinning the distribution of the grant can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/teachers-pay-grant-methodology/teachers-pay-grant-methodology" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/teachers-pay-grant-methodology/teachers-pay-grant-methodology</a>.</p><p>Individual schools’ allocations can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/teachers-pay-grant-2018-to-2019-financial-year-allocations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/teachers-pay-grant-2018-to-2019-financial-year-allocations</a>.</p><p>Further education (FE) and sixth form colleges have a different legal status and relationship to government when compared with academies. They are private sector institutions, independent of government and therefore, we are considering the needs of FE providers separately. We will continue to look carefully at funding for FE in preparation for the next Spending Review.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-01-09T16:18:05.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029378/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029378/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-12-20","Teachers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that teachers in sixth form colleges that (a) are and (b) are not academies receive the same Teachers' pay grant.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","204600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029379","Home Office","false","2019-01-14","<p>A list of countries and territories whose citizens and nationals need a visa prior to travel to the UK as visitors can be found in Appendix 2 to Appendix V of the Immigration Rules - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/immigration-rules/immigration-rules-appendix-v-visitor-rules." target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/immigration-rules/immigration-rules-appendix-v-visitor-rules.</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-01-14T16:30:35.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029379/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029379/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-12-20","Visas: Commonwealth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which Commonwealth countries residents (a) need a visa and (b) do not need a visa to visit the UK for tourism purposes.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","204602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029380","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-11","<p>The Department of Health and Social Care and Home Office officials are continuing to hold discussions on the development of a new joint alcohol strategy and further announcements will be made in due course. There are no plans at this stage to publish an alcohol workforce strategy alongside it.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-01-11T12:00:35.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029380/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029380/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","Alcoholic Drinks: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he plans to publish an alcohol workforce strategy to accompany the alcohol strategy.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","204571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029381","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-11","<p>Public Health England (PHE) assessed alcohol care teams (ACTs) in hospitals in the guidance ‘Local health and care planning: menu of preventative interventions’, which supports local planning processes and informs local commissioning strategies and plans. PHE found ACTs to be an effective and cost-effective option for National Health Service sustainability and transformation partnerships to consider helping reduce the harm to individuals, including to those whose alcohol use impacts most heavily on NHS health services, such as repeat hospital admissions. The guidance is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-health-and-care-planning-menu-of-preventative-interventions" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/local-health-and-care-planning-menu-of-preventative-interventions</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-01-11T11:59:50.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029381/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029381/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","Alcoholic Drinks: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment his Department has made of the (a) effectiveness and (b) cost-effectiveness of alcohol care teams in hospitals.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","204572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029382","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-14","<p>Midwives and other health professionals have a professional duty to keep up to date with evidence based advice on lifestyle issues to support the patients in their care. Every maternity service in the National Health Service is also actively implementing elements of the Saving Babies’ Lives Care Bundle. This programme covers a range of initiatives that seek to raise awareness of the known risk factors among pregnant women and health professionals, including the importance of not drinking alcohol.</p><p> </p><p>Current Nursing and Midwifery Council standards highlight the importance of communicating with women to help them make informed choices about their health and health care. This includes ensuring midwives and healthcare professionals are aware of the UK Chief Medical Officers’ Low Risk Drinking Guidelines. No dedicated funding has been allocated by the Department for this purpose.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England’s Start4Life social marketing programme informs pregnant women of the risks associated with consuming alcohol during pregnancy through its website, social media channels and direct emails. The Start4Life website is available to view at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/start4life/pregnancy/alcohol/" target="_blank">www.nhs.uk/start4life/pregnancy/alcohol/</a></p><p> </p><p>In March 2017, the Government issued guidance setting out how the low risk drinking guidelines can best be communicated on the labels of alcoholic drinks. This guidance sets out the core elements of the guidelines that the Government would wish to see communicated to the public and is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/communicating-the-uk-chief-medical-officers-alcohol-guidelines" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/communicating-the-uk-chief-medical-officers-alcohol-guidelines</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","204574 ; 204575 ; 204576 ; 204577","2019-01-14T16:13:58.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029382/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1029382/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-12-20","Pregnancy: Alcoholic Drinks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to ensure midwives are aware of the Chief Medical Officers’ advice that it is safest not to drink alcohol during pregnancy.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","204573"
